{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509045"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11373"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.45,0.03,0.26,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4018"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4018"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64065"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3758"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man is brought in to the Emergency Department following a two-day history of fever, rigors, and general malaise. Over the same time period, he has had a productive cough. His medical history includes hypertension, paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, and metastatic prostate cancer for which he is undergoing chemotherapy (last cycle 7 days ago). He had coronary artery bypass surgery six years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His blood pressure is 145/90 mmHg, pulse 103/min, temperature 38.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air. An intravenous line is inserted and some investigations got underway.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be of the most value initially?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood cultures","Complete blood count","Electrolytes","Chest X-ray","Quantiferon Gold Test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a febrile patient with a recent history of cancer treated actively with chemotherapy, the primary concern would be febrile neutropenia which is an oncological emergency. Apart from the clinical picture suggesting this diagnosis, a key investigation would be the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete blood count\u003C/strong\u003E. If this showed a low neutrophil count, this would confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with febrile neutropenia should be commenced on empirical broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics as soon as possible (within 30 minutes of presentation). Two sets of \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E should be taken prior to antibiotic treatment and a full septic screen should be enacted as soon as possible (\u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E, urine MCS, respiratory NAT, stool NAT, and investigating any other potential sources e.g. sputum MCS, wound swabs, etc.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is insufficient information in the history to suggest the patient has tuberculosis which could be investigated using the \u003Cstrong\u003EQuantiferon Gold Test\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The diagnosis of febrile neutropenia should be suspected in a patient presenting with a history of fever and recent chemotherapy.","A complete blood count is crucial in evaluating a patient with suspected febrile neutropenia to assess the neutrophil count.","Prompt initiation of empirical broad-spectrum antibiotics is essential in managing febrile neutropenia."],"references":["Punnapuzha S, Edemobi PK, Elmoheen A. Febrile Neutropenia. [Updated 2023 Mar 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541102/","Lucas AJ, Olin JL, Coleman MD. Management and Preventive Measures for Febrile Neutropenia. P T. 2018 Apr;43(4):228-232. PMID: 29622943; PMCID: PMC5871243. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5871243/","Keck JM, Wingler MJB, Cretella DA, Vijayvargiya P, Wagner JL, Barber KE, Jhaveri TA, Stover KR. Approach to fever in patients with neutropenia: a review of diagnosis and management. Ther Adv Infect Dis. 2022 Nov 26;9:20499361221138346. doi: 10.1177/20499361221138346. PMID: 36451936; PMCID: PMC9703488. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9703488/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64065"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:02:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:03:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4018"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78722"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2